:23:"Alo EasyMail Newsletter";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:1;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:15:"easymail update";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"guid";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:78:"http://www.eventualo.net/blog/2012/01/easymail-2-4-new-features-and-some-news/";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:11:"isPermaLink";s:5:"false";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:11:"description";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:362:"EasyMail 2.4: new features Today I&#8217;ve released the new version 2.4 of EasyMail newsletter plugin. Here you are the good news: now it&#8217;s possible to add custom fields into the subscription form, the link clicked inside newsletters are tracked, there is a new database table that contains the unsubscribed email addresses. The custom field feature [...]";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:32:"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/";a:1:{s:7:"creator";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:3:"alo";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:40:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:6653:"<h4>EasyMail 2.4: new features</h4>\n<p>Today I&#8217;ve released the new version <strong>2.4</strong> of EasyMail newsletter plugin.<br />\nHere you are the <strong>good news</strong>: now it&#8217;s possible to add <strong>custom fields</strong> into the subscription form, the <strong>link clicked</strong> inside newsletters are tracked, there is a new database table that contains the <strong>unsubscribed email addresses</strong>.<br />\n<span id="more-1826"></span></p>\n<p>The <strong>custom field feature</strong> was developed for you by <strong>David Comuñas</strong> <em>aka</em> eqhes (website: <a href="http://eutopia.cat" title="visit site" target="_blank">http://eutopia.cat</a>). Many thanks for your hard work, David!<br />\nIn <em>For developers</em> page I&#8217;ve just added a quick info that explains <a href="http://www.eventualo.net/blog/easymail-newsletter-for-developers/#tutorial-customfields">how to add custom fields</a>. Anyway, you can find an example of custom fields inside custom hook file: look for the function called <em>custom_easymail_set_my_custom_fields</em>. (What is that file? <a href="http://www.eventualo.net/blog/easymail-newsletter-for-developers/#custom-hooks">read more</a>).</p>\n<p>About <strong>click tracking</strong>, now the placeholders including a link (post url, site url, read online) will be tracked when clicked. It&#8217;s a good practice, also to have a more accurate feedback than only &#8220;viewed&#8221; tracking.</p>\n<p>Then, now there is a <strong>new database table</strong> that contains the <strong>unsubscribed</strong> email addresses. So, when you mass import new email addresses, the already unsubscribed ones will not be added.</p>\n<p>(Here you are the full <a href="http://wordpress.org/extend/plugins/alo-easymail/changelog/" title="plugin changelog on WP.org" target="_blank">changelog</a>).<br />\nYou can go on WP.org and <a href="http://wordpress.org/extend/plugins/alo-easymail/" target="_blank">download it</a>.<br />\nYou can read guide, faqs&#8230; (see links in right sidebar) and use the <a href="http://www.eventualo.net/forum/">forum</a> to share your feedback. And <strong>you can contribute</strong> to keep the plugin update donating some money to me. </p>\n<form style="display: inline;" action="https://www.paypal.com/cgi-bin/webscr" method="post">\n<input name="cmd" type="hidden" value="_s-xclick" />\n<input name="lc" type="hidden" value="GB" />\n<input name="hosted_button_id" type="hidden" value="9E6BPXEZVQYHA" />\n<input style="border: 0pt none;" alt="PayPal" name="submit" src="https://www.paypal.com/en_US/i/btn/btn_donate_SM.gif" type="image" /> <img src="https://www.paypal.com/it_IT/i/scr/pixel.gif" border="0" alt="" width="1" height="1" /><br />\n</form>\n<h4>EasyMail 2.4: where are the .PO???</h4>\n<p>From 2.4 there are not <strong>.po</strong> files inside plugin package that now is a bit lighter. If you like to create or update a translation you can go to <a href="http://code.google.com/p/alo-easymail/" title="visit site" target="_blank">/code.google.com/p/alo-easymail</a>, the translation project powered by <strong>László Viktor</strong>. There you can download files and join the translation group. Share your files!</p>\n<h4>A bug with a lot of subscribers</h4>\n<p>The problem: the plugin admin pages are not loaded properly. You can see only the top admin bar, the main menu, maybe the page title&#8230; but not the page content.<br />\nThere is an issue if you have a large number of subscribers. The number could be 5.000, or 10.000, or more, it depends on your server operation timeouts.<br />\nInfact, in plugin admin pages (settings, subscriber list, edit newsletter screeen) the plugin counts the subscribers in each lists. If you have several lists, it does the count several times&#8230; and if you have a lot of subscribers the page could not be loaded because it&#8217;s counting&#8230; I&#8217;ll try to fix in future releases.<br />\nFor now you can try to increase your server timeouts:<br />\n- in your <strong>wp-config.php</strong> add these lines:</p>\n\n<div class="wp_syntax"><div class="code"><pre class="php" style="font-family:monospace;"><span style="color: #990000;">define</span><span style="color: #009900;">&#40;</span><span style="color: #0000ff;">''WP_MEMORY_LIMIT''</span><span style="color: #339933;">,</span> <span style="color: #0000ff;">''96M''</span><span style="color: #009900;">&#41;</span><span style="color: #339933;">;</span>\n<span style="color: #339933;">@</span><span style="color: #990000;">ini_set</span><span style="color: #009900;">&#40;</span> <span style="color: #0000ff;">''upload_max_size''</span><span style="color: #339933;">,</span> <span style="color: #0000ff;">''100M''</span> <span style="color: #009900;">&#41;</span><span style="color: #339933;">;</span>\n<span style="color: #339933;">@</span><span style="color: #990000;">ini_set</span><span style="color: #009900;">&#40;</span> <span style="color: #0000ff;">''post_max_size''</span><span style="color: #339933;">,</span> <span style="color: #0000ff;">''105M''</span><span style="color: #009900;">&#41;</span><span style="color: #339933;">;</span>\n<span style="color: #339933;">@</span><span style="color: #990000;">ini_set</span><span style="color: #009900;">&#40;</span> <span style="color: #0000ff;">''max_execution_time''</span><span style="color: #339933;">,</span> <span style="color: #0000ff;">''600''</span> <span style="color: #009900;">&#41;</span><span style="color: #339933;">;</span></pre></div></div>\n\n<p>- in your <strong>.htaccess</strong> (in blog root: if this file does not exist, create it) add these lines:</p>\n\n<div class="wp_syntax"><div class="code"><pre class="php" style="font-family:monospace;">php_value memory_limit 96M\nphp_value upload_max_filesize 100M\nphp_value post_max_size 105M\nphp_value max_execution_time <span style="color: #cc66cc;">600</span>\nphp_value max_input_time <span style="color: #cc66cc;">600</span></pre></div></div>\n\n<p>Otherwise, in the meantime, if you think to manage a so large number of subscribers I suggest that you use a <strong>professional service</strong> like mailchimp, phplist, campaignmonitor ecc. (and you can find plugins that help you to integrate them in your blog).</p>\n<h4>The subscription form&#8230;</h4>\n<p>&#8230;is very old-style. It uses tables and not a modern html layout, sack library and not jquery. It&#8217;s one of the oldest part of the plugin and I&#8217;d like to rewrite it, also in order to make it more clean and customisable. It&#8217;s in <em>todo</em> list for next releases.</p>\n<h4>100.000!</h4>\n<p>More than 100.000 plugin 